12	1	When responding in an interview, it's crucial to be clear and concise while also showcasing your passion and expertise. Use the STAR method—Situation, Task, Action, Result—to structure your answers effectively. This approach not only keeps your responses focused but also demonstrates your problem-solving skills and the impact of your work.	answer	\N	{"knowledge_base_influence": {"sources": [{"id": 1, "title": "Design Sprint Map for Heroes", "category": "Blog Post", "confidence": "90.0", "word_matches": ["form"], "content_snippet": "Write who they will meet along their journey in stack formation (in order top to bottom) to complete their goal", "relevance_score": 36.629999999999995}, {"id": 2, "title": "The Action", "category": "Blog Post", "confidence": "90.0", "word_matches": ["form"], "content_snippet": "**Assumption:**\\r\\n   Our users don't trust our application with their bank information", "relevance_score": 36.629999999999995}, {"id": 3, "title": "Lego MVP Warm-up", "category": "Blog Post", "confidence": "90.0", "word_matches": [], "content_snippet": "As Product Designers we build MVPs often", "relevance_score": 0.0}], "avg_relevance": 24.4, "sources_count": 3, "raw_confidence": "90.0", "influence_level": "minimal", "confidence_score": "22.0", "has_knowledge_base_content": false}}	2025-09-01 02:36:52.084917	2025-09-01 02:36:52.084917
