14	1	Building strong teams is all about pulling in the right people and creating an environment that fosters growth and collaboration. I focus on coaching rather than dictating, encouraging my team to think bigger and explore multiple approaches to problems. When everyone understands the "why" behind their work and feels empowered to contribute, it leads to innovative solutions and a more cohesive team dynamic.	answer	\N	{"knowledge_base_influence": {"sources": [{"id": 92, "title": "Balancing Speed and Quality", "category": "Blog Post", "confidence": "90.0", "word_matches": ["build", "teams"], "content_snippet": "5 years for completion\\n- **Goal**: Validate feasibility before committing significant resources\\n\\n## Task\\n\\n- Ship something quickly to validate continued investment in the ambitious idea\\n- Gather evidence to support solution direction\\n- Persuade other teams to prioritize and support the project\\n\\n## Action\\n\\n### Initial Resistance\\n\\n- During a crucial area-leads-to-group-leads meeting, an EM and PDM insisted it needed to be a big project\\n- Technical risk was perceived as huge to get it right\\n- I immediately challenged the \\"no\\" response\\n\\n### Strategic Intervention\\n\\n- With support from partners, I pushed for \\"break it down, regardless of risk\\"\\n- Asked EM, PM, and PDM to present scope of risk instead of blocking\\n- Team returned with not only risk scope but solutions to each one\\n\\n### Risk Mitigation Examples\\n\\n- Instead of building for each platform, they'd use a small Beta group\\n- Used good communication and design to set expectations\\n- Challenged team to present what they could validate in just six weeks\\n\\n### Speed as Constraint\\n\\n- Framed speed as a constraint to push the idea forward\\n- Validated potential without massive upfront investment\\n- Engineering Manager Abraham took the challenge and created a plan\\n\\n## Result\\n\\n### Breakthroughs Achieved\\n\\n- Designers broke down problem and scope into manageable parts\\n- Engineers identified specific constraints and dependencies that could be avoided\\n- Instead of complete solution for new membership types, rolled out alpha version to select willing adopters\\n\\n### Platform Strategy\\n\\n- Acknowledged certain benefits wouldn't work on certain platforms (mobile, desktop, tablet)\\n- Team reduced estimated timeline and dependencies\\n- Delivered scrappy alpha for specific customers\\n\\n### Quality Focus\\n\\n- When only a portion of work was valuable, they could hone in on quality\\n- Allowed scaling impact because the solution was so useful\\n- Demonstrated that speed constraints can lead to better quality outcomes\\n\\n## Key Lessons\\n\\n1", "relevance_score": 100}, {"id": 113, "title": "Leadership Lessons from Product Design", "category": "Blog Post", "confidence": "90.0", "word_matches": ["build", "teams"], "content_snippet": "## Team Development\\n\\n### Building Strong Teams\\n\\n- Pull in the right people for specific challenges\\n- Create opportunities for growth and learning\\n- Foster collaboration between designers and product managers\\n\\n### Coaching Techniques\\n\\n- Use frameworks to push teams beyond obvious solutions\\n- Encourage exploration of multiple approaches\\n- Help teams reframe problems to be more ambitious\\n\\n## Strategic Alignment\\n\\n### Executive Communication\\n\\n- Present evidence-backed innovation proposals\\n- Position design work as strategic differentiators\\n- Secure alignment before major initiatives\\n\\n### Navigating Change\\n\\n- Guide teams through strategic pivots\\n- Maintain vision while adjusting execution\\n- Ensure continuity during organizational changes", "relevance_score": 100}], "avg_relevance": 100, "sources_count": 2, "raw_confidence": "90.0", "influence_level": "high", "confidence_score": "90.0", "has_knowledge_base_content": true}}	2025-09-01 03:32:45.202294	2025-09-01 03:32:45.202294
