7	Designing For Flow	One of my favorite concepts is flow. Flow is a state in which you are working, and nothing else matters. It's that span of time that felt like 5 minutes, but could have been 50.\r\n\r\nMihály Csíkszentmihályi wrote a book about it in the 90's - it's full of great studies, findings and insights about the attributes of activity that put people into flow. Even better, it suggests the flow might equal happiness. \r\n\r\nWhen I first encountered flow, around 2011, I was seeking an understanding of how to love ones work. It took me several years, many podcasts, many other books and a second reading of Csíkszentmihályi's book to catch the connection with design and flow. \r\n\r\nIt was obvious now that I look back, but because I was seeking an answer about how I could find flow, I wasn't looking at how I could design situations for other people to be in flow. I create experiences, solutions and interfaces constantly. People interact with my work on a daily basis - can I use flow to improve their lives?\r\n\r\nWhen I first approached designing for flow, I questioned the motivation. Was I going to use flow to improve my app's retention metric so I could prove that the app had value? Or, was I using the principals of flow to create a great and engaging experience for the user to bring them joy. It was important to me that I was transparent - even if just to myself for the moment. I didn't want any hidden agenda.\r\n\r\nAs I worked through the question internally, I came to a relatively simple solution to keep me on the right track when designing. I looked at all of the elements of flow, and asked myself with each one, is this for the user or for the application? \r\n\r\nThe elements of flow:\r\n\r\n* A clear goal\r\n* A concentrated field\r\n* Immediate feedback\r\n* The balance between using your skills and being challenged\r\n* A feeling of control\r\n* Ease of the journey\r\n* An altered perception of time\r\n\r\nWhen I design a solution for a person's problem, I try my best to empathize with them. I want to understand their pain points, and design solutions that help remove those pain points and let them achieve their goals.\r\n\r\nwas I helping them transparently achieve their goal, or was I putting them on a path that lead them to achieving my goal, not theirs. As a good designer, this should come natural\r\n\r\n\r\n[Flow](http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/66354.Flow)\r\n[The 8 Elements of Flow](http://www.flowskills.com/the-8-elements-of-flow.html)\r\n\r\n[Flow White Paper](https://web.cs.wpi.edu/~gogo/courses/imgd5100/papers/FlowQuestionnaire.pdf]	f	2017-03-27 02:05:00	2017-03-27 02:05:39.948296	2017-04-02 15:19:32.736261		designing-for-flow	\N	\N
